Acting National Police Commissioner Khomotso Phahlane says the apparent kidnapping of a month old baby amounted to an abuse of state resources. JOHANNESBURG - Acting National Police Commissioner Khomotso Phahlane says the apparent kidnapping of one-month-old Siwaphiwe Mbambo, who was found on Sunday morning, amounted to an abuse of state resources. This comes after the arrest of the mother. On Friday, the mother reported her baby missing citing that she had been snatched by two armed men while breast feeding her at the side of the road. Phahlane says resources which were used in searching for the child could have better been used somewhere else to curb crime. The South African Police Service supported by law enforcement officers and scores of concerned community members, spent...Phahlane says he is disappointed that those involved took advantage of their fellow South African s trust by making false claims, which left the nation in a state of sorrow and anxiety. Sibongile Mbambo, the mother of the month old infant, is currently in custody for her alleged role in orchestrating the kidnapping of the little girl. Phahlane says a special prosecutor was appointed on Sunday morning to work with the South African Police Service on the case.(Edited by Zamangwane Shange)